<H1>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </H1>
<H1>EJB</H1>
<ul>
  <li><font size="5">A Java-specific component model that operates in the 
  context of Java 2 Enterprise Edition application architecture</font></li>
  <li><font size="5">Based on a specification which is implemented as 
  application servers (<a href="http://www.bea.com/framework.jsp?CNT=index.htm&FP=/content/products/server">BEA 
  WebLogic</a>, IBM WebSphere, iPlanet Application Server) and databases (Oracle 
  8i, 9i, Sybase jaguar, IBM DB2)</font></li>
  <li><font size="5">Flexible (Providing message-driven EJB) and portable 
  (introducing an EJB query syntax to replace proprietary mechanisms)</font></li>
  <li><font size="5">EJB server provides the underlying support for security, 
  transactions etc and is shared between all EJBs</font></li>
  <li><font size="5">Two primary EJB types:</font></li>
  <li><font size="5">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; session beans: conceptually similar to 
  transactional COM+ components</font></li>
  <li><font size="5">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; entity beans: a mapping of underlying 
  data and are intended to be longer-lived</font></li>
</ul>
<span class="body">
<p><font size="5" face="Times New Roman" color="#000080">&quot;The EJB 2.1 
specification enhances the EJB architecture with support for Web services. 
Enterprise developers can implement and deploy Web service applications with the 
same level of ease as other server-side applications.</font></p>
<p><font size="5" face="Times New Roman" color="#000080">In addition, EJB 2.1 
provides a container-managed Timer Service; enhancements to EJB QL -- the 
declarative language for container-managed persistence -- to support aggregate 
and order-by operations; and a generalization of message-driven beans to support 
additional messaging types.</font></p>
<p><font size="5" face="Times New Roman"><font color="#000080">The EJB 2.1 
specification effort is being conducted as </font>
<a href="http://jcp.org/jsr/detail/153.jsp" style="color: #000080">JSR-153</a><font color="#000080"> 
under the Java Community Process (JCP) program.&quot; </font></font></p>
<p><font color="#000080" size="5" face="Times New Roman">-- java.sun.com</font></p>
</span>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

